<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName authority="Murray, 1907" authorityName="Murray" authorityYear="1907" class="Heterotardigrada" family="Echiniscidae" genus="Echiniscus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Echiniscus perarmatus" order=" Echiniscoidea" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="perarmatus">Echiniscus perarmatus Murray, 1907</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Material examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
21 specimens, CBUMAG:TAR:00098 (7 specimens), 00099 (10 specimens), 00101 (4 specimens). Microhabitat: lichen from the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Parmeliaceae" genus="Parmotrema" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Parmotrema" order="Lecanorales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Parmotrema</taxonomicName>
, growing on a tree trunk. Localities: Bella Vista, Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta, 
<geoCoordinate direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="1" value="11.096611">11°05'47.8&quot;N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="1" value="-74.08456">74°05'04.4&quot;W</geoCoordinate>
, 1930 m a.s.l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
The morphological characters of the Colombian specimens agree with the original description of 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. perarmatus" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" rank="species" species="perarmatus">E. perarmatus</taxonomicName>
(Murray, 1907). This species, according to the literature, has a tropical and subtropical distribution; with the type locality, Cape Colony (South Africa), it has also been recorded in Indonesia, Hawaii, United States, and Venezuela (
<bibRefCitation author="McInnes, SJ" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="257 - 352" title="Zoogeographic distribution of terrestrial / freshwater tardigrades from current literature." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222939400770131" volume="28" year="1994">McInnes 1994</bibRefCitation>
). The apparent wide distribution we suggest indicates 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. perarmatus" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" rank="species" species="perarmatus">E. perarmatus</taxonomicName>
might be a species complex. Therefore further work with original material, or specimens from the type locality, would be required to solve this problem.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="2">This is the first record (sensu lato) for Colombia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
